== WHEN IS PITOCIN RECOMMENDED?

Pitocin serves several distinct purposes in obstetric care. Understanding when and why it's used helps you evaluate whether it's appropriate in your situation.

=== Labor Induction

When continuing the pregnancy poses greater risks than delivery, Pitocin can initiate labor. Medical indications include:

- Post-term pregnancy (42+ weeks) with increasing stillbirth risk
- Premature rupture of membranes without labor onset (infection risk rises with time)
- Preeclampsia or gestational hypertension
- Gestational diabetes with poor glucose control
- Cholestasis of pregnancy
- Low amniotic fluid (oligohydramnios)
- Intrauterine growth restriction
- Concerning fetal heart rate patterns or decreased fetal movement

In these situations, the risk of waiting for spontaneous labor clearly outweighs the risks of induction. Pitocin can be genuinely life-saving.

=== Labor Augmentation

When labor has started on its own but contractions are too weak, too infrequent, or have stalled, Pitocin can strengthen and regulate contractions. About 31% of women who gave birth vaginally received Pitocin to augment their labors.

Augmentation is considered when:
- Contractions are infrequent, irregular, or weak
- Cervical dilation has stopped progressing
- The baby is not descending through the birth canal
- Labor extends beyond expected timeframes for the stage

=== Third Stage of Labor (After Delivery)

After your baby is born, Pitocin is routinely given to help the uterus contract, expel the placenta, and clamp down on blood vessels to prevent hemorrhage. Uterine atony (loss of muscle tone) causes 70-80% of all postpartum hemorrhage, one of the leading causes of maternal death worldwide.

When given prophylactically during the third stage, Pitocin reduces the risk of postpartum hemorrhage by approximately 40%. The WHO, ACOG, and AWHONN all recommend routine oxytocin administration during the third stage.

=== Post-Cesarean

Following a cesarean delivery, Pitocin is administered to help the uterus contract and prevent excessive bleeding, serving the same hemorrhage-prevention purpose as third-stage use.

