== MAKING YOUR DECISION

=== Questions to Ask Your Provider

1. _Why are you recommending Pitocin right now?_ (Is there a clear medical indication, or is this routine/convenience-based?)
2. _What are the specific risks in my situation?_
3. _What alternatives can we try first?_
4. _What happens if we wait an hour and reassess?_
5. _What dose will you start with, and how quickly will you increase it?_
6. _Can we stop the Pitocin once I'm in active labor (around 6 cm)?_
7. _What monitoring will be in place?_

=== Factors That Favor Accepting Pitocin

- Clear medical indication (preeclampsia, post-term, ruptured membranes, fetal concerns)
- Labor has truly arrested despite trying alternatives
- The benefit of delivery clearly outweighs the risks of continued waiting
- Third-stage hemorrhage prevention (strong evidence, low risk)
- You've been given adequate information and have given genuine informed consent

=== Factors That Favor Declining or Asking to Wait

- No clear medical indication; recommendation is based on timing or convenience
- Labor is slow but still progressing (slow doesn't mean stalled)
- Alternatives haven't been tried (walking, position changes, nipple stimulation, rest)
- You're hoping for an unmedicated birth and understand the endorphin implications
- You don't feel you've received adequate information or time to decide
- Your cervix is unfavorable (Bishop score below 6), reducing the likelihood of successful induction

